+<h2>Sequencing Guiding Principles</h2>
+<div class="guiding">
+  <h3>1. Lead with AI to Create the Moat</h3>
+  <p>AI-powered capabilities ship in Q1 alongside foundation work, not after it. The autonomous setup agent, AI flow generation surfaces, and conversational editing are the first visible signals that automation is getting smarter. By Q3, agentic per-user treatment and AI-guided channel selection open the biggest strategic whitespace in marketing automation: no competitor continuously optimizes message, channel, timing, and incentive per individual profile in real time. AI creates the compounding performance loop that becomes our primary competitive moat and the switching cost that grows with every flow cycle.</p>
+</div>
+<div class="guiding">
+  <h3>2. Fix the Foundation to Protect ~$X.XM in Automation Revenue</h3>
+  <p>Builder instability, batch-processing lag, reporting inaccuracy, and multi-surface confusion are actively eroding trust. ~$X.XK/mo in HVC MRR has been cited in automation-specific pain themes. CJB churn is compounding. These fixes are concentrated in Q1&ndash;Q2 because every AI demo backfires when customers discover &ldquo;Automations Not Sending&rdquo; and &ldquo;my flow timing is an hour late.&rdquo; The paid cohort target depends on CSAT recovery and churn reduction, both of which require the automation foundation to be solid first.</p>
+</div>
+<div class="guiding">
+  <h3>3. Invest in Trigger Depth &amp; Activation to Deliver the Aha Moment</h3>
+  <p>CJB Activation is 33.6% and FTU 30-day turn-on is 6.8% &mdash; most new users never send their first automation. Trigger depth is why operators choose Klaviyo (5&times; more triggers). Industry templates, the autonomous setup agent (URL to flows in 3 clicks), auto-build on store-connect, and the searchable template gallery all exist to compress time-to-first-automation from weeks to minutes. The $X.XM in unrealized automation ARR depends on delivering the aha moment before customers give up.</p>
+</div>
+
